      "id": "E2-09-Q1",
      "type": "short-answer",
      "totalMarks": 3,
      "commandWord": "find",
      "difficulty": "easy",
      "questionText": "A straight-line graph passes through the points $(2, 5)$ and $(6, 13)$.\n\n(a) Find the gradient of the line.\n(b) Find the equation of the line.",
      "answerType": "expression",
      "correctAnswer": "(a) 2, (b) $y = 2x + 1$",
      "tolerance": null,
      "unit": null,
      "markScheme": [
        {
          "mark": "M1",
          "desc": "Gradient $= \\dfrac{13-5}{6-2} = \\dfrac{8}{4} = 2$"
        },
        {
          "mark": "A1",
          "desc": "(a) Gradient $= 2$"
        },
        {
          "mark": "A1",
          "desc": "(b) $y = 2x+1$ cao (using $y-5=2(x-2)$)"
        }
      ],
      "workingSteps": [
        "(a) Gradient $= \\dfrac{13-5}{6-2} = \\dfrac{8}{4} = 2$",
        "(b) $y-5 = 2(x-2) \\Rightarrow y = 2x-4+5 = 2x+1$",
        "Check $(6,13)$: $2(6)+1=13$ ✓"
      ],
      "explanation": "Use gradient formula then substitute a point to find the $y$-intercept."
    },
    {
      "id": "E2-09-Q2",
      "type": "short-answer",
      "totalMarks": 4,
      "commandWord": "find",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "questionText": "The graph of $y = mx + c$ passes through $(0, -3)$ and is parallel to the line $y = 4x + 7$.\n\n(a) Write down the gradient.\n(b) Write down the $y$-intercept.\n(c) Find the $x$-coordinate of the point where the line crosses the $x$-axis.\n(d) Find where the line $y = mx + c$ intersects the line $y = -x + 9$.",
      "answerType": "expression",
      "correctAnswer": "(a) 4, (b) -3, (c) 0.75, (d) (2.4, 6.6)",
      "tolerance": null,
      "unit": null,
      "markScheme": [
        {
          "mark": "B1",
          "desc": "(a) Gradient $= 4$ (parallel lines have equal gradients)"
        },
        {
          "mark": "B1",
          "desc": "(b) $y$-intercept $= -3$"
        },
        {
          "mark": "M1",
          "desc": "(c) $0 = 4x-3 \\Rightarrow x = 0.75$"
        },
        {
          "mark": "A1",
          "desc": "(d) $4x-3=-x+9 \\Rightarrow 5x=12 \\Rightarrow x=2.4$; $y=6.6$"
        }
      ],
      "workingSteps": [
        "(a) Parallel to $y=4x+7$, so gradient $=4$; equation: $y=4x-3$",
        "(b) Passes through $(0,-3)$, so $y$-intercept $=-3$",
        "(c) Set $y=0$: $4x-3=0 \\Rightarrow x=\\frac{3}{4}=0.75$",
        "(d) $4x-3=-x+9 \\Rightarrow 5x=12 \\Rightarrow x=2.4$; $y=-2.4+9=6.6$"
      ],
      "explanation": "Parallel lines share the same gradient; use the given point to determine $c$."
    },
